West Muskingum Families,
We are very excited to announce that West Muskingum Schools has partnered with FinalForms, an online forms and data management service that replaces paper forms. FinalForms allows you to complete and sign enrollment, back-to-school and athletic participation forms for your students.
FinalForms also saves data from season-to-season and year-to-year, meaning that you will never have to enter the same information twice! FinalForms also pre-populates information wherever possible for each of your students, saving you time.
You can review your data at any time to verify it is current. You will be required to sign your forms once per year and after any update,‚Ä¶ More

PARENTS OF WEST MUSKINGUM MIDDLE SCHOOL ONLINE LEARNERS:

On the evening of Tuesday, August 25, you will have access to a Google Classroom for online learners. This classroom will contain schedules and other information for your student's first day of school. It is accessible through the student portal of the West Muskingum website.

Students will need their West Muskingum emails to log onto Google Classroom. You will also be receiving a phone call from a West Muskingum staff member either today or tomorrow. During this call, you will receive your student's log-in information, if needed, along with the opportunity to ask questions.

We look forward to the start of the school year and appreciate your patience as we roll out our new and improved online learning.

Mrs. Lindsay Rayner
Principal

From the Athletic Department:

Each athlete will receive a number of ticket vouchers prior to an athletic event. Each voucher will allow the holder to purchase a ticket at the gate. One voucher will equal one ticket purchased.

The number of vouchers given to each athlete is dependent on the number of spectators allowed inside a facility and the number of athletes on each team. You must have a voucher to purchase a ticket. No passes will be accepted which include senior citizen passes.

If you have any questions, contact the athletic department at 452-6312.

Ted Harrison

post_text:
West Muskingum Parents,
The district's reopening plan was released last Wednesday and can be found on the district website at www.westmschools.org. We ask that you take the short survey on the final page in order for us to make plans for the 2020-21 school year. Please complete a separate survey for each school-aged child in your family by Friday, Aug. 7.
We have answered many questions through email and on Facebook, before and after the plan was released. We know that there are still questions to be answered. Waiting on Governor DeWine, the Ohio Department of Education, Ohio Department of Health, and the Ohio High School Athletic Association to give us answers has been grueling this summer and we understand your frustration, as we are constantly playing the waiting game too.
I invite you to join me in a Facebook live information session this Wednesday, Aug. 5 from 7:30 to 8:30 p.m., to answer any questions you may have so I can to help you make an informed decision.

Chad Shawger
Superintendent

Please complete a separate survey for each school-aged child in your family by Friday, Aug. 7.
We have answered many questions through email and on Facebook, before and after the plan was released. We know that there are still questions to be answered. Waiting on Governor DeWine, the Ohio Department of Education, Ohio Department of Health, and the Ohio High School Athletic Association to give us answers has been grueling this summer and we understand your frustration, as we are constantly playing the waiting game too.
I invite you to join me in a Facebook live information session this Wednesday, Aug. 5 from 7:30 to 8:30 p.m., to answer any questions you may have so I can to help you make an informed decision.

Chad Shawger
Superintendent

post_text:
Planning for next school year

West Muskingum Schools will review the plan to restart schools in the fall and will be making a formal announcement as soon as possible. Please know that our goal is to have students with us in the building on a full time basis if possible. With that being said, we know that some families will require an online option for students with underlying conditions. We will be providing that option as well. This will be a process with a never ending list of things to consider, so we ask for your patience as we continue to work through this.

As we work together with our community, we believe we can open school in person and keep students and staff safe. We will be releasing information as we get it through our usual platforms.



Thank you,
Chad Shawger
Superintendent

Mrs. Rayner

Chad Shawger
Superintendent

West Muskingum Families,
On Monday Governor DeWine ordered our physical buildings closed through at least May 1. Our teachers are still working from home and will continue to provide lessons for our students.
We will still observe Spring Break from April 9-13 as these days of remote learning are counting toward student hours.
Each Monday, will continue our Grab and Go food distribution for those in need. Be sure to register each week on the district website from noon on Thursday through Saturday at noon.
There are many unknowns at this time. Please excuse the many All Calls, but I want all of you to have the information as we get it.
If you have any questions or concerns, please reach out to an administrator or teacher for clarification.
Stay safe West.
Chad Shawger
Superintendent

post_text:
Good evening,
There will be a Grab and Go event each Monday from 11 am to noon at the high school. Bagged meals will include breakfast and lunch for five days.

Please register online each week so we can have an accurate count. The registration link is located on the district website at www.westmschools.org. Registration will be open until noon on Saturday.

I want to thank our families for what you are doing at home to support the educational process. Our teachers are working from home, so please email them with any questions or concerns. We certainly don‚Äôt expect you to teach the content, but please partner with us to be sure learning is still taking place.

Nobody is certain how long this will last, but everyone is doing their best and we will get through this together. We all miss our students and want to get back to normal as soon as possible.

As always, if you have questions all employee emails are on the website or you can call the district office at 455-4052 and leave a voicemail.

Stay healthy West Muskingum,
Chad Shawger
Superintendent

post_text:
Congratulations to West Muskingum's Tina Jones on receiving the Coalition of Rural and Appalachian Schools (CORAS) Support Staff Award.

A 27-year employee of West Muskingum, Mrs. Jones was nominated by Superintendent Chad Shawger. She received her award during CORAS' January meeting at Ohio University-Zanesville. She was also recognized by the West Muskingum Board of Education for her award.

CORAS, in partnership with the Ohio University Gladys W. and David H. Patton College of Education, is an organization of 110 school districts and other educational institutions in the 32-county region of Ohio designated as Appalachia. The mission of CORAS is to advocate for and support the public schools of Appalachia Ohio in the continuous improvement of educational opportunities available to all the region's children.

Students will use this unit as a foundation for the ankle unit coming up next and discuss various ankle injuries that can occur.

Five West Muskingum High School student/athletes were among 80 students participating in the Muskingum Valley Leadership/Sportsmanship Summit hosted by Zane State College on Tuesday.

Tornadoes Harley Hopkins, Connor Paima, Mariska McCune, Hayley Barker, and Kyle Reilly participated in team building activities, discussions about what leadership and sportsmanship means to them, and how they will continue to spread the importance of friendly competition.

Earlier this year, 14 students from across the region were selected as 2019-20 Athlete Leadership/Sportsmanship Ambassadors. Representing West Muskingum was senior Hayley Barker.

Congratulations to each of these student/athletes.

post_text:
The Ohio State University Extension Office recently presented Real Money, Real World, a financial literacy program, at West Muskingum Middle School. This curriculum is time tested and has been highly successful because of the creative community efforts of extension and school educators, and the business community. There are four classroom lessons and an interactive spending simulation that provides the opportunity to make lifestyle and budget choices similar to those made by 27-year-old adults.

Classroom lessons include how education and occupation affect income, paycheck deductions, checking and savings accounts, and a spending budget. Students are randomly given a job with a salary, spouse, and children to set up the simulation.

OSU Extension Office and community members run the spending booths such as housing, child care, insurance, and transportation, so students can take their salary and try to purchase the items needed and wanted for a month of living. Thank you to the extension office and community members for their participation.

post_text:
Jena Maxwell, West Muskingum 2017 graduate, earned her American FFA Degree at the 92nd National FFA Convention and Expo this past weekend. West Muskingum FFA has had 11 students earn this honor since the chapter formed in 1968, nine of which were earned since 2014.

According to West Muskingum Agricultural Education Teacher Jeremy Ryan, for those students who earn their American Degree, this is the culmination of up to six years of work, community service, local, district, state and national activities, and leadership. Out of over 700,000 FFA members, less than 1% earn this honor.

"The skills that these students have developed will follow them throughout their lives and have helped to develop them into the wonderful young men and woman that they are. This is not something that is easy to attain but can be achieved by setting a goal and working towards it," said Ryan. "Although this will be the last time that they wear their FFA jacket, they will always have the memories of this day and the knowledge and skills needed to be successful adults.‚Äù

Congratulations Jena!
